## job_store.py — Specific Implementation Rules

The pull-mutate-push pattern inside every write function is intentional and must not
be simplified. The sequence is: acquire `_write_lock`, call `_pull_from_hub()` to get
the current state, apply the mutation to the in-memory copy, call `_push_to_hub()` to
write the full updated state back. The lock prevents two concurrent chunk writes from
interleaving their pull-mutate-push cycles, which would cause one to overwrite the
other's mutation (a lost update). Never replace this pattern with a single-field patch
call, because the Hub dataset repo API does not support atomic partial updates.

The `_push_to_hub()` function must retry on HTTP 429 with exponential backoff and must
NOT retry on any other HTTP error. A 404 means the repo does not exist (operator
configuration error — raise immediately). A 403 means the token lacks write permission
(operator configuration error — raise immediately). A 500 means the Hub had an internal
error — raise immediately with a clear message so the job is marked failed and the
user is notified. Only 429 is a retryable condition.

The `force_download=True` parameter in `_pull_from_hub()` is mandatory. Without it,
the HF Hub client may serve a locally cached copy of the jobs JSON that does not
reflect mutations made by other processes. On a free-tier Space there is only one
process, but the parameter must still be set as a defensive measure against future
multi-worker deployments.

