## cache.py — Specific Implementation Rules

The cache must be seeded from `job_store.load_all_jobs()` at startup before any
Gradio request can be processed. In `app.py`, this must happen at module import time,
not inside the first request handler. If the seed fails (Hub unreachable at startup),
the cache starts empty and logs a warning — it does NOT raise and does NOT prevent
the app from starting.

The `put()` function must be called after every successful `job_store.*` write call.
The pattern in `app.py` is: call `job_store.update_job_chunk()` → immediately call
`cache.put(job_id, record)` with the returned record. If you add a new `job_store`
function, you must add the corresponding `cache.put()` call at every call site.

The `get_system_status()` function must not count completed or failed jobs in the
active or queued tallies. Only "processing" jobs count as active; only "queued" jobs
count as queued. A job in "complete" or "failed" status is finished and must not
contribute to load level calculations.

